8. DISCUSSION
=================================================

8.1 Strengths
- High accuracy (87%) with Random Forest
- Preserved full dataset through mean imputation
- Explainable predictions via feature importance
- Professional UI with role-based authentication
- Batch processing capability for clinics
- Comprehensive analytics dashboard
- Complete preprocessing pipeline documented in teaching notebook

8.2 Limitations
- Dataset size limited (292 samples after cleaning)
- Binary classification only (no multi-class severity)
- Simple mean imputation (not advanced methods like MICE)
- No real-time EHR integration
- Generalizability to other populations unknown
- Database removed for simplicity (session state used instead)

8.3 Clinical Implications
- Decision support tool for doctors (NOT replacement for medical judgment)
- Explainable AI builds trust with healthcare professionals
- Batch processing enables screening programs
- PDF reports integrate with existing clinical workflows
- Early detection can significantly improve patient outcomes

8.4 Technical Insights
- Random Forest excels due to ensemble nature (reduces overfitting)
- Feature scaling critical for SVM performance
- Mean imputation preserves dataset integrity
- 10-fold CV provides robust evaluation with limited data
- Feature importance helps doctors understand model decisions

