APPENDIX B: DEFENSE Q&A
=================================================
Q: "Why mean imputation over other methods like KNN or MICE?"
A: "Mean imputation is simple, fast, and works well for numerical medical data. 
   More complex methods add complexity without guaranteed better results for this 
   dataset size (292 samples). For larger datasets, advanced methods could be explored."

Q: "Why 10-fold CV instead of 5-fold?"
A: "10-fold provides more reliable accuracy estimates and better utilizes the 
   limited dataset. With only 292 samples, 5-fold would use only 58 samples 
   per test fold, increasing variance in performance estimates."

Q: "Why did you remove the database?"
A: "We simplified the architecture for academic demonstration. The focus is on 
   ML preprocessing techniques and model comparison. Database integration is standard 
   but not core to ML learning objectives. Streamlit's session state works for our 
   educational purpose."

Q: "How does SHAP/Feature Importance improve your project?"
A: "It moves from 'black box' to 'glass box' AI. Doctors can see WHY 
   the model made a prediction (e.g., 'cholesterol level contributed 30% 
   to this prediction'), building trust with medical professionals."

Q: "Why Random Forest over other models?"
A: "Random Forest achieved highest accuracy (87%) and CV score. Its ensemble 
   nature reduces overfitting, and it provides built-in feature importance. SVM 
   was close second (85%) but requires more hyperparameter tuning."

Q: "How do you handle class imbalance?"
A: "The dataset is relatively balanced (164 no-disease vs. 139 disease). If imbalance 
   were severe, we would use techniques like SMOTE, ADASYN, or adjust class 
   weights in the algorithms."

